The Meaning of the Name u-Kama

The name u-Kama comes from the Shona word ukama (often written hukama), meaning relationship, kinship, and interdependence. In this worldview the world is not composed of isolated resources but of relationships linking people, animals, plants, places, ancestors, and spirits. Responsibility arises from participation within these relationships rather than from ownership.
Similar ideas appear across many indigenous knowledge systems. Among the Ju/’hoansi San, anthropologists describe the concept of n!oresi, a relational bundle connecting people, animals, landscapes, and stories within a particular place. Land is therefore understood not as property but as a living network of obligations.
The choice of the name u-Kama reflects this relational understanding. It signals that the system is built around continuity of relationships between humans and the living world, rather than around the extraction or financialisation of nature.
In simple terms, u-Kama recognises that ecological systems endure only when the relationships that sustain them are honoured across generations.

